WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.919 --> 00:00:08.460
STEVEN ROTHSTEIN:
Welcome, everybody.

00:00:08.460 --> 00:00:11.580
It's my great
pleasure to introduce

00:00:11.580 --> 00:00:15.690
Eric, recently from
Citizen Schools.

00:00:15.690 --> 00:00:18.770
I met Eric about five
or six years ago.

00:00:18.770 --> 00:00:21.780
And there were two things
that really stood out.

00:00:21.780 --> 00:00:24.510
I was there at Citizen
Schools because we

00:00:24.510 --> 00:00:27.244
had several volunteers
from Google who had really

00:00:27.244 --> 00:00:29.160
engaged with the program
and was very excited.

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:30.340
And I was told
hey, why don't you

00:00:30.340 --> 00:00:31.550
reach out and find out
what they're doing?

00:00:31.550 --> 00:00:33.716
And there were two things
that struck me right away.

00:00:33.716 --> 00:00:37.580
One is how incredibly
analytic they are.

00:00:37.580 --> 00:00:40.010
And they talk about
measures and outcomes,

00:00:40.010 --> 00:00:42.190
and it was like I was at Google.

00:00:42.190 --> 00:00:43.410
It was really interesting.

00:00:43.410 --> 00:00:47.750
And then the second thing
was, everybody was amazing,

00:00:47.750 --> 00:00:49.100
Eric himself included.

00:00:49.100 --> 00:00:51.130
It's just an amazing
group of people.

00:00:51.130 --> 00:00:53.590
And I felt like I was
at home, even though I

00:00:53.590 --> 00:00:57.906
wasn't inside
Google at the time.

00:00:57.906 --> 00:01:00.030
We started to have a closer
and closer relationship

00:01:00.030 --> 00:01:01.130
with Citizen Schools.

00:01:01.130 --> 00:01:03.790
We became one of the biggest
contributor of volunteers

00:01:03.790 --> 00:01:10.590
to the program, the after school
program, extended learning.

00:01:10.590 --> 00:01:15.375
And I really felt good about
the work that we had done.

00:01:15.375 --> 00:01:17.625
And then I personally got
involved in public education

00:01:17.625 --> 00:01:20.295
and wanting to change it to
introduce computer science.

00:01:20.295 --> 00:01:23.600
And I really learned
how amazingly difficult

00:01:23.600 --> 00:01:26.180
is to change public education.

00:01:26.180 --> 00:01:29.290
And so if there are two things
that stand out now about Eric,

00:01:29.290 --> 00:01:35.160
one is the incredible courage
it takes to have a vision

00:01:35.160 --> 00:01:39.270
and turn it into a
program that you really

00:01:39.270 --> 00:01:43.790
want to institute major change
in how education is done.

00:01:43.790 --> 00:01:45.330
And not just turning
around schools,

00:01:45.330 --> 00:01:48.120
but actually engaging
broadly with schools.

00:01:48.120 --> 00:01:54.690
And the second piece
is the tenacity.

00:01:54.690 --> 00:01:58.860
I think he founded Citizen
Schools in '95 I think.

00:01:58.860 --> 00:02:01.832
So that's almost 20
years of working on this.

00:02:01.832 --> 00:02:03.540
And I just think the
commitment that that

00:02:03.540 --> 00:02:07.320
takes with such a difficult
program of introducing

00:02:07.320 --> 00:02:09.479
something truly new into
the public school systems

00:02:09.479 --> 00:02:09.978
is amazing.

00:02:09.978 --> 00:02:12.750
And it's not just something
that's going on in Boston.

00:02:12.750 --> 00:02:13.990
It's not something that's just
going on in Massachusetts.

00:02:13.990 --> 00:02:16.710
It's going on in several
states across the country.

00:02:16.710 --> 00:02:18.490
And scaling the
organization's what's

00:02:18.490 --> 00:02:20.840
really the big
initiative right now.

00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:26.260
So he's written a book called
"The Opportunity Equation."

00:02:26.260 --> 00:02:27.660
It wasn't the easiest name.

00:02:27.660 --> 00:02:29.100
It wasn't my first choice.

00:02:29.100 --> 00:02:34.070
But the book is available
to you for $10 over here,

00:02:34.070 --> 00:02:35.500
which is a subsidized price.

00:02:35.500 --> 00:02:38.190
Obviously it's available
on Google Play.

00:02:38.190 --> 00:02:41.030
Google Books is a phenomenal
place to read digital content.

00:02:41.030 --> 00:02:44.240
So at some point, that would be
a good consideration as well.

00:02:44.240 --> 00:02:47.261
It's my great pleasure to
introduce Eric Schwarz.

00:02:47.261 --> 00:02:52.182
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:52.182 --> 00:02:53.390
ERIC SCHWARZ: That's awesome.

00:02:53.390 --> 00:02:55.990
Steven, thank you so much.

00:02:55.990 --> 00:02:57.930
I learned from
Steven many things

00:02:57.930 --> 00:03:02.070
about data, about heart,
building a great culture.

00:03:02.070 --> 00:03:05.720
Learned that you could wear
jeans to work every day too.

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:08.320
Now that I've moved on from the
CEO role of Citizen Schools,

00:03:08.320 --> 00:03:11.140
I'm getting more
comfortable with.

00:03:11.140 --> 00:03:13.840
But I want to thank, before
getting into the book

00:03:13.840 --> 00:03:15.980
and what it's
about, thank really

00:03:15.980 --> 00:03:18.830
the people of Google,
which is what's

00:03:18.830 --> 00:03:21.080
made this relationship amazing.

00:03:21.080 --> 00:03:22.550
And we've built a
relationship that

00:03:22.550 --> 00:03:25.175
started in Mountain View,
grew here in Cambridge,

00:03:25.175 --> 00:03:27.050
was really the next
place where it took hold,

00:03:27.050 --> 00:03:30.392
and now it's in New York,
and Chicago, and other parts

00:03:30.392 --> 00:03:31.350
of the country as well.

00:03:31.350 --> 00:03:35.090
And we've had probably
about 1,000 Googlers,

00:03:35.090 --> 00:03:37.680
many in this office,
others across the country,

00:03:37.680 --> 00:03:38.810
who've gotten involved.

00:03:38.810 --> 00:03:41.440
And the heart
connection as well as

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:44.140
the brain connection to
the work has been awesome.

00:03:44.140 --> 00:03:47.780
I hope it is a growing
experience for the Googlers

00:03:47.780 --> 00:03:50.610
who mentor kids in
Citizen Schools.

00:03:50.610 --> 00:03:54.520
I know it is for the students
as I saw an email this morning

00:03:54.520 --> 00:03:57.210
with Alan Su, who is a
colleague with many of you

00:03:57.210 --> 00:03:59.780
here in Cambridge who was one
