00:37:08.590 --> 00:37:11.200
and the incredible turnaround
it had going from something that

00:37:11.200 --> 00:37:13.766
was about to be closed to
something that actually got

00:37:13.766 --> 00:37:15.890
a lot of national praise
for how strong of a school

00:37:15.890 --> 00:37:18.730
it was after a couple years of
Citizen Schools being involved.

00:37:18.730 --> 00:37:21.912
What are some of your favorite
turnaround stories of not just

00:37:21.912 --> 00:37:24.120
individual students having
breakthroughs, but schools

00:37:24.120 --> 00:37:26.460
like that having breakthroughs,
and a school level

00:37:26.460 --> 00:37:29.440
change that your program
has been able to help with?

00:37:29.440 --> 00:37:31.180
ERIC SCHWARZ: That's
great, thank you.

00:37:31.180 --> 00:37:33.450
So a couple I mentioned
are homegrown right here.

00:37:33.450 --> 00:37:36.770
Edwards was the first, and I
just alluded to a little bit

00:37:36.770 --> 00:37:38.610
in the talk.

00:37:38.610 --> 00:37:41.050
But this was a school
that as Travis mentioned,

00:37:41.050 --> 00:37:43.960
was very close to
being closed down.

00:37:43.960 --> 00:37:47.020
In a three year period before
they started Expanded Learning

00:37:47.020 --> 00:37:52.260
Time, there were 53 assaults
of teachers by students.

00:37:52.260 --> 00:37:55.260
It was the lowest or second
lowest performing school

00:37:55.260 --> 00:37:59.470
on all the different metrics,
test scores and parent demand,

00:37:59.470 --> 00:38:01.760
across the Boston system.

00:38:01.760 --> 00:38:03.637
And they didn't get
a new principle,

00:38:03.637 --> 00:38:05.720
they had they had some
turnover in their teachers,

00:38:05.720 --> 00:38:07.820
but not wholesale turnover.

00:38:07.820 --> 00:38:10.630
What they got was a
9 and 1/2 hour day.

00:38:10.630 --> 00:38:13.870
What they got is every kid
in middle school taking

00:38:13.870 --> 00:38:15.877
four apprenticeships a year.

00:38:15.877 --> 00:38:17.960
What they got is every kid
in middle school having

00:38:17.960 --> 00:38:21.590
an extra hour of math
instruction every day

00:38:21.590 --> 00:38:23.570
led by Citizen School's
AmeriCorps members.

00:38:23.570 --> 00:38:26.510
And that combination
of the extra academics,

00:38:26.510 --> 00:38:29.490
the extra enrichment
totally changed

00:38:29.490 --> 00:38:30.865
things, the spirit
of the school.

00:38:30.865 --> 00:38:33.198
They had a football team,
they had a cheerleading squad.

00:38:33.198 --> 00:38:35.740
Spirit of the school
took off, and it

00:38:35.740 --> 00:38:38.770
went to one of the most
oversubscribed schools,

00:38:38.770 --> 00:38:42.480
big waiting list, erased
80% of the achievement gap

00:38:42.480 --> 00:38:45.860
with suburban
schools in English,

00:38:45.860 --> 00:38:49.340
and reverse the
achievement gap in math.

00:38:49.340 --> 00:38:52.260
And that was the first
school turnaround

00:38:52.260 --> 00:38:55.030
story that convinced
us as an organization

00:38:55.030 --> 00:38:58.490
we need to move from working
with some kids in the school

00:38:58.490 --> 00:39:00.100
to working with all kids.

00:39:00.100 --> 00:39:03.250
And that can really then be
not only an innovative model

00:39:03.250 --> 00:39:05.520
around the edges of
public education,

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:09.870
but a fundamental change to the
offering of public education

00:39:09.870 --> 00:39:12.220
and really bringing
into urban schools

00:39:12.220 --> 00:39:15.380
and integrating within them a
lot of what upper middle class

00:39:15.380 --> 00:39:18.660
families have managed
to create in combination

00:39:18.660 --> 00:39:21.850
with public schools
in their communities.

00:39:21.850 --> 00:39:24.440
A couple years after
that, Orchard Gardens

00:39:24.440 --> 00:39:26.370
replaced the Edwards as
the lowest performing

00:39:26.370 --> 00:39:27.840
school in Boston.

00:39:27.840 --> 00:39:30.900
It was in the bottom five
or six performing schools

00:39:30.900 --> 00:39:33.060
in the whole state
of Massachusetts.

00:39:33.060 --> 00:39:35.030
And that became a
turnaround school.

00:39:35.030 --> 00:39:36.530
So there actually
were a fair amount

00:39:36.530 --> 00:39:39.350
of new teachers in that school.

00:39:39.350 --> 00:39:42.940
But also, they moved to
a 10 hour learning day.

00:39:42.940 --> 00:39:45.270
And at the middle school
level, Citizen Schools

00:39:45.270 --> 00:39:47.050
was the lead partner.

00:39:47.050 --> 00:39:49.110
And while they've had
a real improvement

00:39:49.110 --> 00:39:51.344
across all the grades,
K through eight school,

00:39:51.344 --> 00:39:53.010
the middle school
grades have taken off.

00:39:53.010 --> 00:39:55.610
And it went from being one
of the lowest performing

00:39:55.610 --> 00:40:00.860
schools in Boston to literally
the highest growth scores

00:40:00.860 --> 00:40:03.230
of any school in the
state of Massachusetts

00:40:03.230 --> 00:40:05.877
three years after doing
Expanded Learning Time.

00:40:05.877 --> 00:40:07.210
So that was an incredible story.

00:40:07.210 --> 00:40:10.660
We now have-- the new
principal at that school,

00:40:10.660 --> 00:40:13.470
is a former Citizen
Schools campus director.

00:40:13.470 --> 00:40:15.420
She worked at the
McCormick School,

00:40:15.420 --> 00:40:17.410
and that's sort of
early stage turnaround.

00:40:17.410 --> 00:40:19.990
But I know a lot of Googlers
have worked at the McCormick.

00:40:19.990 --> 00:40:22.440
That's where we
started 20 years ago.

00:40:22.440 --> 00:40:25.060
And that school, the data
that's about to come out

00:40:25.060 --> 00:40:28.630
on the MCAS in sixth, and
seventh, and eighth grade,

00:40:28.630 --> 00:40:31.550
amazing growth scores-- some of
the highest in the city, some

00:40:31.550 --> 00:40:33.510
of the highest in the
state for a school

00:40:33.510 --> 00:40:36.770
that also was not too far
away from being closed,

00:40:36.770 --> 00:40:38.410
and really struggling.

00:40:38.410 --> 00:40:41.620
There've been others in
East Palo Alto, in Chicago

00:40:41.620 --> 00:40:45.730
last year, our kids showed
almost two full years

00:40:45.730 --> 00:40:48.700
of learning growth as
opposed to typical of one

00:40:48.700 --> 00:40:51.550
year across four schools
that were in Chicago.

00:40:51.550 --> 00:40:53.840
So a number of
schools, and we're

00:40:53.840 --> 00:40:57.060
excited to now have a handful
of school superintendents.

00:40:57.060 --> 00:41:00.020
If Cambridge joins the list,
that'd be great, saying we

00:41:00.020 --> 00:41:01.500
want to make this normal.

00:41:01.500 --> 00:41:03.314
We want to invest in this.

00:41:03.314 --> 00:41:04.980
We know it's not going
to come for free,

00:41:04.980 --> 00:41:06.720
but we want to
think differently.

00:41:06.720 --> 00:41:08.930
We want to really think
outside of the box

00:41:08.930 --> 00:41:11.947
and not tinker with
the school system.

00:41:11.947 --> 00:41:13.280
That's what generally gets done.

00:41:13.280 --> 00:41:15.580
People just add a little
bit, subtract a little bit,

00:41:15.580 --> 00:41:17.550
the budget's pretty
much next year

00:41:17.550 --> 00:41:21.550
what it was last year,
but think much differently

00:41:21.550 --> 00:41:24.030
and really think about a
much longer learning day, not

00:41:24.030 --> 00:41:25.550
a little bit longer
learning day.

00:41:25.550 --> 00:41:27.580
Much different
set of activities,

00:41:27.580 --> 00:41:29.410
whole different talent model.

00:41:29.410 --> 00:41:32.460
And we now have proof positive
in the 30 plus schools

00:41:32.460 --> 00:41:35.360
that when you do that, even
with some of the toughest

00:41:35.360 --> 00:41:37.400
to reach kids in
some of the toughest

00:41:37.400 --> 00:41:38.850
neighborhoods in
the country, you

00:41:38.850 --> 00:41:41.060
can deliver outstanding results.

00:41:41.060 --> 00:41:43.890
So thanks Travis,
